Exploring Number of Words and Other Characteristics of Messages Received

Time of message being logged vs message length for different app types, with a line representing overall mean message length

Plot 1

Messages sent on messaging apps seem to be longer than those sent on social media apps, after 3pm. There are small peaks in the number of words in a message at around 10am, 1pm and after dinner, this make sense as it is time when people are likely to either be on a break or not at work/school.

Time of message being logged vs message length from regular and non-regular contacts, with a line representing overall mean message length

Second plot

Messages sent by regular contacts seem to have more variance compared to those from non-regular contacts, with lots of 0 word messages, and a some very long messages.The longest messages were received by regular contacts at night, which makes sense as people are likely to be off work/school and may have time to do things like tell stories at night. There are a large number of zero word messages sent by regular contacts and none by non-regular contacts, this makes sense as people you don’t usually talk to generally need to give context or an explanation as to why they are sending something even if they are sending a post, while memes and posts being sent by friends often doesn’t need any text accompanying it.

Counts of various message lengths compared to the median number of words in a message

Third plot

The median number of messages is close to zero. There are much higher counts of short messages (under 30ish words) than longer messages, which makes sense as messaging is usually a short form of contacting someone, and things that take more words to communicate may either be sent as an email or be a phone call. There are three messages of over 90 words. These are likely either stories of rants.

Number of words in a message for regular and non-regular contacts and some key summary stats

Fourth plot

All messages from non-regular contacts had between 10 and 40 words, while the number of words in messages from regular contacts had a much wider range, with many messages containing zero words and one containing over 250. The mean number of words is greater than the median for both regular and non-regular contacts, but the gap is larger for regular contacts, this makes sense as this group sent many short and zero word messages, and some very long messages, as regular contacts can send informal messages that contain few words or long stories and do not need to worry so much about messaging ettiquette.
